    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="la">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName ref="#mansuetus"><expan><abbr>Fl</abbr><ex>avius</ex></expan> Ma<supplied reason="omitted">n</supplied>suetus</persName> <w xml:id="w1"><choice><reg>biarchus</reg><orig>biar<choice><corr>c</corr><sic>l</sic></choice>us</orig></choice></w>, qui milita
                    <lb n="2" break="no"/><choice><reg>vit</reg><orig>bit</orig></choice> in numero leonum seniorum,
                    <lb n="3"/>de proprio suo arcam sibi posuit. Si
                    <lb n="4"/>quis eam aperire voluerit, dabit fisci
                    <lb n="5"/>viribus <measure type="fine" unit="roman_pound" commodity="silver" quantity="10">argenti pondo d<supplied reason="omitted">e</supplied>cem</measure>; qu<choice><corr>a</corr><sic>e</sic></choice>m
                    <lb n="6"/>arcam vet<supplied reason="omitted">e</supplied>ranibus <w xml:id="w2">c<choice><corr>o</corr><sic>u</sic></choice>mmendavi<supplied reason="omitted">t</supplied></w>.
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <app loc="1" from="#w1" to="#w1">
                    <lem><choice><reg>biarchus</reg><orig>biar<choice><corr>c</corr><sic>l</sic></choice>us</orig></choice></lem>
                    <rdg source="#bertolini1874a #bertolini1874b #bertolini1875b #cilv8755 #ilcv515">biarcus</rdg>
                </app>
                <app loc="6" from="#w2" to="#w2">
                    <lem>c<choice><corr>o</corr><sic>u</sic></choice>mmendavi<supplied reason="omitted">t</supplied></lem>
                    <rdg source="#lettich1983">commendavi</rdg>
                </app>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p><persName ref="#mansuetus" xml:lang="la">Flavius Mansuetus</persName>, <term ref="#biarchus" xml:lang="la">biarchus</term> who served in the <term xml:lang="la">numerus</term> of the <term xml:lang="la">Leones seniores</term>, set up this <term xml:lang="la">arca</term> at his own expense.</p>
                <p>Should anyone wish to open it, he shall pay ten pounds of silver to the <term xml:lang="la">fiscus</term>; (he) entrusted this <term xml:lang="la">arca</term> to the veterans.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it">
                <p><persName ref="#mansuetus">Flavio Mansueto</persName>, <term ref="#biarchus" xml:lang="la">biarchus</term> che militò nel <term xml:lang="la">numerus</term> dei <term xml:lang="la">Leones seniores</term>, pose l'arca a proprie spese.</p>
                <p>Se qualcuno vorrà aprirla, verserà al <term xml:lang="la">fiscus</term> dieci libbre (romane) d'argento; (egli) affidò quest'arca ai veterani.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en">
                <p>
                    <persName ref="#mansuetus" xml:lang="la">Flavius Mansuetus</persName> was a <term ref="#biarchus" xml:lang="la">biarchus</term> of the <term xml:lang="la">Leones seniores</term>. The <term xml:lang="la">biarchus</term> represented one of the lowest positions among the junior officer ranks, whose function remains almost entirely unknown. According to <persName>Grosse</persName>, the <term xml:lang="la">biarchus</term> would have been a non-commissioned officer in charge of provisions, corresponding to the ancient <term xml:lang="la">frumentarius</term>, perhaps based on the etymological origin of the name from <g xml:lang="grc">βίος</g> + <g xml:lang="grc">ἀρχός</g> or <g xml:lang="grc">βία</g> + <g xml:lang="grc">ἀρχός</g> (<ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#grosse1920">Grosse 1920, 114-115</ref>). <persName>Speidel</persName> argues instead that the term <term xml:lang="la">biarchus</term> derived etymologically from <term xml:lang="la">exarchus</term>, a rank attested in the 3rd century AD, and performed the same functions; in fact, the rank of <term xml:lang="la">exarchus</term> could be granted twice to the same soldier as a reward, earning him the title of <term xml:lang="la">bis exarchus</term>, which in the 4th century became <term xml:lang="la">biarchus</term> (<ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#speidel2005">Speidel 2005, 206</ref>).
                </p>
                <p>
                    The <term xml:lang="la">auxilium palatinum</term> of the <term xml:lang="la">Leones seniores</term> is recorded as being stationed in Gaul (<ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#nd">ND occ. 5, 171; 7, 65</ref>).
                </p>
                <p>
                    According to the site plan, the sarcophagus of <persName ref="#mansuetus" xml:lang="la">Mansuetus</persName> is contiguous with that of <ref target="./marcaridus.xml"><persName xml:lang="la">Flavius Marcaridus</persName></ref>, <roleName type="military" ana="#tribunus" xml:lang="la">tribunus</roleName> of the <term xml:lang="la">Iovii iuniores</term>. The reason why the burials of members of two different <term xml:lang="la">numeri</term> were placed side-by-side remains unclear, as it is a unique case within the necropolis; perhaps this proximity is not due to human activity, but to a shift caused by the flooding of the <placeName>Lemene</placeName> river.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName ref="#mansuetus" xml:lang="la">Mansuetus</persName> entrusted the protection of his burial to the veterans. As noted by <persName>Lettich</persName>, this declaration is one of many clues suggesting a permanent garrison of troops in <placeName>Concordia</placeName> (<ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#lettich1983">Lettich 1983, 91</ref>).
                </p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" xml:lang="it">
                <p>
                    <persName ref="#mansuetus" xml:lang="la">Flavius Mansuetus</persName> era un <term ref="#biarchus" xml:lang="la">biarchus</term> dei <term xml:lang="la">Leones seniores</term>. Il <term ref="#biarchus" xml:lang="la">biarchus</term> rappresentava una delle più basse cariche tra i gradi subalterni, la cui funzione risulta quasi del tutto ignota. Secondo <persName>Grosse</persName>, il <term xml:lang="la">biarchus</term> sarebbe stato un sottufficiale addetto al vettovagliamento e corrispondente all'antico <term xml:lang="la">frumentarius</term>, forse basandosi sull'origine etimologica del nome derivata da <g xml:lang="grc">βίος</g> + <g xml:lang="grc">ἀρχός</g> oppure <g xml:lang="grc">βία</g> + <g xml:lang="grc">ἀρχός</g> (<ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#grosse1920">Grosse 1920, 114-115</ref>). <persName>Speidel</persName> sostiene invece che il termine derivasse etimologicamente da <term xml:lang="la">exarchus</term>, carica attestata nel III secolo d.C.; la funzione di <term xml:lang="la">exarchus</term> poteva essere conferita due volte allo stesso soldato come premio, ottenendo il titolo di <term xml:lang="la">bis exarchus</term>, che nel IV secolo divenne <term xml:lang="la">biarchus</term> (<ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#speidel2005">Speidel 2005, 206</ref>).
                </p>
                <p>
                    L'<term xml:lang="la">auxilium palatinum</term> dei <term xml:lang="la">Leones seniores</term> risulta stanziato in Gallia (<ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#nd">ND occ. 5, 171; 7, 65</ref>).
                </p>
                <p>
                    Dalla planimetria, il sarcofago di <persName ref="#mansuetus" xml:lang="la">Mansuetus</persName> risulta contiguo a quello di <ref target="./marcaridus.xml"><persName xml:lang="la">Flavius Marcaridus</persName></ref>, <roleName type="military" ana="#tribunus" xml:lang="la">tribunus</roleName> degli <term xml:lang="la">Iovii iuniores</term>. Non risulta chiaro il motivo per il quale le sepolture di membri di due <term xml:lang="la">numeri</term> diversi fossero addossate, caso unico all'interno della necropoli; forse tale vicinanza non è dovuta a cause antropiche, ma a uno spostamento causato dalle esondazioni del fiume <placeName>Lemene</placeName>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName ref="#mansuetus" xml:lang="la">Mansuetus</persName> affida la tutela della propria sepoltura ai veterani. Come nota <persName>Lettich</persName>, tale dichiarazione costituisce uno dei tanti indizi che suggeriscono uno stanziamento stabile di truppe a <placeName>Concordia</placeName> (<ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#lettich1983">Lettich 1983, 91</ref>).
                </p>
